@node "Install" "Installation"
To install SplitMultiImage, simply drag the icon to the location of your
choice - there are no additional files that need installing.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@{b}Starting SplitMultiImage@{ub}

SplitMultiImage may be started from Workbench or the shell, and can be used
via AmiDock too.  In either case, if no arguments are specified a file
requester will be displayed allowing you to select multiple files which
you'd like to try to split.

When starting from the shell, multiple filenames may be specified on the
command-line, and SplitMultiImage will act on all those files.

Similarly, you may select the icons of image files on the Workbench and
shift-click the SplitMultiImage icon those files will be split, rather than
popping up a file requester.

Press Ctrl-C in the output window or shell, while SplitMultiImage is
working, to abort.

@{b}How it works@{ub}

SplitMultiImage reads the file(s) and if it's recognised by the datatype
system as an image, it decodes the first image.  If it is then determined
that the file contains more than one image, each image will then be saved
as a new file (in the same directory as the original file) with the name
@{i}filename@{ui}.@{i}nnn@{ui}.ilbm, where @{i}filename@{ui} is the original filename and @{i}nnn@{ui} is a
number between 1 and 999, denoting the image number.

For example: splitting a 3 page TIFF fax file named 'fax1.tif' creates:

  fax1.tif.001.ilbm
  fax1.tif.002.ilbm
  fax1.tif.003.ilbm

You can then view the individual files in your favourite image viewer.
@endnode

